</div>
</div>
<p>Ruhollah Musavi Khomeini was born to Mustafa Musawi<sup id="cite_ref-khoalgix_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-khoalgix-10" title=""><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup> and Hajiyah Aga Khanum in the town of <a href="/wiki/Khomein" title="Khomein">Khomein</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-moin2_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-moin2-11" title=""><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup> about 300 kilometers (180 miles) south of <a href="/wiki/Tehran" title="Tehran">Tehran</a>, on<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12" title=""><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup> September 24, 1902.<sup id="cite_ref-birth1_0-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-birth1-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-birth2_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-birth2-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Khomeini is called a <i><a href="/wiki/Sayyid" title="Sayyid">sayyid</a></i> as his family traces its descent from the seventh of the <a href="/wiki/Imamah_(Shia_doctrine)" title="Imamah (Shia doctrine)" class="mw-redirect">Twelve Imams</a>, <a href="/wiki/Musa_al-Kazim" title="Musa al-Kazim" class="mw-redirect">Musa al-Kazim</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-moin2_11-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-moin2-11" title=""><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13" title=""><span>[</span>14<span>]</span></a></sup> Several of his close ancestors were dedicated to Islamic studies: his father and both of his grandfathers were all <a href="/wiki/Shia_Islam" title="Shia Islam">Shia</a> clerics.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14" title=""><span>[</span>15<span>]</span></a></sup> Khomeini's paternal grandfather, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Sayid_Ahmad_Musawi_Hindi&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Sayid Ahmad Musawi Hindi (page does not exist)">Sayid Ahmad Musawi Hindi</a>, spent many years in <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a> before returning to Persia to purchase a home in Khomein that his family would own until the late twentieth century.<sup id="cite_ref-khoalgix_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-khoalgix-10" title=""><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15" title=""><span>[</span>16<span>]</span></a></sup> <sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16" title=""><span>[</span>17<span>]</span></a></sup> Khomeini's father was murdered when he was still an infant. Khomeini's supporters assert that Khomeini's father was killed by <a href="/wiki/Reza_Shah" title="Reza Shah">Reza Shah</a>, however this Shah would not come to power for another twenty-six years.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17" title=""><span>[</span>18<span>]</span></a></sup> Many historians today believe his father may have been the victim of a local dispute.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18" title=""><span>[</span>19<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19" title=""><span>[</span>20<span>]</span></a></sup> Khomeini's mother and one of his aunts proceeded to raise him until 1918, when both of them died.<sup id="cite_ref-moin18_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-moin18-20" title=""><span>[</span>21<span>]</span></a></sup> Ruhollah Khomeini began to study the <a href="/wiki/Qur%27an" title="Qur'an">Qur'an</a>, <a href="/wiki/Islam" title="Islam">Islam's</a> holiest book, and elementary <a href="/wiki/Persian_language" title="Persian language">Persian</a> at age six <sup id="cite_ref-rei311_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rei311-21" title=""><span>[</span>22<span>]</span></a></sup>. The following year, he began to attend a local school, where he learned mathematics, science, geography, and other traditional subjects.<sup id="cite_ref-moin18_20-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-moin18-20" title=""><span>[</span>21<span>]</span></a></sup> Throughout his childhood, he would continue his religious and secular education with the assistance of his relatives, including his mother's cousin, Ja'far,<sup id="cite_ref-moin18_20-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-moin18-20" title=""><span>[</span>21<span>]</span></a></sup> and his elder brother, Morteza Pasandideh.<sup id="cite_ref-mil85_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mil85-22" title=""><span>[</span>23<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>After <a href="/wiki/World_War_I" title="World War I">World War I</a> arrangements were made for him to study at the Islamic seminary in <a href="/wiki/Esfahan" title="Esfahan" class="mw-redirect">Esfahan</a>, but he was attracted instead to the seminary in <a href="/wiki/Arak,_Iran" title="Arak, Iran">Arak</a>, under the leadership of <a href="/wiki/Ayatollah" title="Ayatollah">Ayatollah</a> <a href="/wiki/Abdul_Karim_Haeri_Yazdi" title="Abdul Karim Haeri Yazdi">Abdul Karim Haeri Yazdi</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23" title=""><span>[</span>24<span>]</span></a></sup> In 1920, Khomeini moved to Arak and commenced his studies.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24" title=""><span>[</span>25<span>]</span></a></sup> The following year, Ayatollah Haeri Yazdi transferred the Islamic <b>seminary</b> to the holy city of <a href="/wiki/Qom" title="Qom">Qom</a>, southwest of Tehran, and invited his students to follow. Khomeini accepted the invitation, moved,<sup id="cite_ref-mil85_22-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mil85-22" title=""><span>[</span>23<span>]</span></a></sup> and took up residence at the Dar al-Shafa school in Qom.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25" title=""><span>[</span>26<span>]</span></a></sup> Khomeini's studies included Islamic law (<i><a href="/wiki/Sharia" title="Sharia">sharia</a></i>) and jurisprudence (<i><a href="/wiki/Fiqh" title="Fiqh">fiqh</a></i>)<sup id="cite_ref-rei311_21-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rei311-21" title=""><span>[</span>22<span>]</span></a></sup>, but by that time, Khomeini had also acquired an interest in poetry and philosophy (<i><a href="/wiki/Irfan" title="Irfan">irfan</a></i>). So, upon arriving in Qom, Khomeini sought the guidance of <a href="/wiki/Mirza" title="Mirza">Mirza</a> Ali Akbar Yazdi, a scholar of philosophy and mysticism. Yazdi died in 1924, but Khomeini would continue to pursue his interest in philosophy with two other teachers, Javad Aqa Maleki Tabrizi and Rafi'i Qazvini.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26" title=""><span>[</span>27<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-bru46_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bru46-27" title=""><span>[</span>28<span>]</span></a></sup> However, perhaps Khomeini's biggest influences were yet another teacher, Mirza Muhammad 'Ali Shahabadi,<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28" title=""><span>[</span>29<span>]</span></a></sup> and a variety of historic <a href="/wiki/Sufism" title="Sufism">Sufi</a> <a href="/wiki/Mysticism" title="Mysticism">mystics</a>, including <a href="/wiki/Mulla_Sadra" title="Mulla Sadra">Mulla Sadra</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ibn_Arabi" title="Ibn Arabi">Ibn Arabi</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-bru46_27-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bru46-27" title=""><span>[</span>28<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table class="infobox vcard" cellpadding="2" style="border-color: #cef2e0; width:26em; font-size: 85%">
<tr>
<th bgcolor="#CEF2E0" align="center" colspan="2" style="border-bottom:1px solid #cef2e0; font-size: 125%;"><a href="/wiki/Muslim_scholar" title="Muslim scholar" class="mw-redirect">Muslim scholar</a><br /></th>
</tr>
